# ✅ How to Defend

## 1️⃣ Output Encoding (BEST defense for both)

### ✅ SAFE (Thymeleaf / React)



```jsx
<p>{comment}</p>
```

✅ Escapes HTML & JS automatically

***

## 2️⃣ Avoid Dangerous APIs

❌ Never use:

```java
th:utext
innerHTML
document.write
```

✅ Use:

```js
textContent
```

***

## 3️⃣ Content Security Policy (Stops XSS)

```http
Content-Security-Policy:
  default-src 'self';
  script-src 'self';
```

✅ Even if XSS slips through, JS won’t execute

***

## 4️⃣ HttpOnly Cookies (Limits XSS damage)

```http
Set-Cookie: session=abc; HttpOnly;
```

✅ Cookies can’t be stolen via JS\
❌ XSS still dangerous, but impact reduced

***

# ❌ Common Myths (VERY IMPORTANT)

❌ “HTML Injection is harmless”\
✅ It can become XSS easily

❌ “Input validation prevents XSS”\
✅ Output encoding prevents XSS

❌ “CSP replaces output encoding”\
✅ CSP is a safety net, not a fix

***

# 🧠 Interview‑Ready Summary

✅ HTML Injection inserts **markup**\
✅ XSS executes **code**\
✅ HTML Injection affects appearance\
✅ XSS affects control & security\
✅ All XSS is injection\
✅ Not all injection is XSS

***

# ✅ Final Rule (MEMORIZE)

    If user input can execute JavaScript → XSS (critical)
    If user input only changes HTML → HTML Injection (lower risk)
    Always encode output

